\section{\texorpdfstring{{Introduction}}{Introduction}}\label{sec-intro}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{{Data
Overview}}{Data Overview}}\label{sec-data-overview}

In this report, we will begin using logistic regression to model
outcomes of interest that take one of two categorical values. Then, we
will use model diagnostics to assess if this model is the most reliable
and fits the data best. Then we will look at the \texttt{DAProject.csv}
dataset which contains the socio-economic and lifestyle factors from the
2013 - 2016 Scottish Health Surveys.

In this report, we will use the data stored in \texttt{DAProject5.csv}
which has 7 variables and 14,018 individuals. \texttt{DAPprojects.csv}
contains the following columns:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  \texttt{Age} - Age of individual,
\item
  \texttt{Sex} - Sex of individual (Male/ Female),
\item
  \texttt{Education} - Highest educational qualification of individual,
\item
  \texttt{Veg} - Consume recommended daily vegetable intake (Yes / No),
\item
  \texttt{Fruit} - Consume recommended daily fruit intake (Yes / No),
\item
  \texttt{Year} - Year of the Scottish Health Survey,
\item
  \texttt{Obese} - Indicator of individuals obesity classification (Yes
  / No).
\end{itemize}

Since this dataset contains a binary categorical variable \texttt{Obese}
- classified as \texttt{Yes}/\texttt{No} - logistic regression may be
considered as an appropriate modelling approach. The main questions of
interest are:

\begin{itemize}
\item
  Has the prevalence of obesity in Scotland changed over the given years
  of the Scottish Health Survey?
\item
  Are there any differences in obesity by age, gender, socio-economic
  status, or lifestyle factors?
\end{itemize}

\section{\texorpdfstring{{Explanatory Data
Analysis}}{Explanatory Data Analysis}}\label{sec-explanatory-data-analysis}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{{Logistic
Regression}}{Logistic Regression}}\label{sub-sec-log-reg}

Logistic regression is used when the outcome of interest takes one of
two categorical values (e.g.~\texttt{Yes}/\texttt{No}). In this case,
the response variable takes the value 1 (defined as success, with
probability \(p_i\)) or 0 (defined as failure, with probability
\(1 - p_i\)). And the response is given by \(Y_i\) with Bernoulli
distribution. The corresponding model uses the logit link function:
\begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq-log-odds}{
g(p_i) = 
\log\left(\frac{p_i}{1 - p_i}\right)
= \log\left(\frac{\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)}{\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 0 \mid \underline{x}_i)}\right)
= \underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta}
}\end{equation}

We can refer to Equation~\ref{eq-log-odds} as the log-odds, since
\(\frac{p_i}{1 - p_i}\) represents the odds. Taking the inverse of the
logit link function gives the following:
\begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq-odds-1}{
\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)
= \frac{\exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}{1 + \exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}
}\end{equation}
\begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq-odds-0}{
\mathbb{P}(Y_i = 0 \mid \underline{x}_i)
= \frac{1}{1 + \exp(\underline{x}_i^\top \underline{\beta})}.
}\end{equation}

