\section{\texorpdfstring{{Formal Data
Analysis}}{Formal Data Analysis}}\label{sec-formal-data-analysis}

\subsection{\texorpdfstring{{Model
Specification}}{Model Specification}}\label{sub-sec-model-specification}

We will now fit a logistic model to investigate the relationship between
obesity and explanatory variables. Let \(Y_i = 1\) if individual
\emph{i} is obese and \(Y_i = 0\) otherwise. We will assume that:
\[Y_i \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p_i)\]where,
\(p_i = \mathbb{P}(Y_i = 1 \mid \underline{x}_i)\) and
\(Y_i = Obese_i\). The model is given by:
\begin{equation}\protect\phantomsection\label{eq-year-model}{logit(p_i)=\alpha_0 + \beta_1 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2014)}
+ \beta_2 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2015)}
+ \beta_3 \,\mathbb{I}_{(\text{Year}_i = 2016)}}\end{equation}

where: 2013 is the reference year. The intercept \(\alpha_0\) represents
the log-odds of an individual being obese in the reference year 2013,
and the coefficients \(\beta_1\), \(\beta_2\), \(\beta_3\) represent the
change in log-odds in each year compared to 2013.

To fit a logistic regression model, we will conduct variable selection
using a backwards elimination approach, supported by model selection
critera such as Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC) and likelihood
ratio test. The performance of the model we select will be assessed
using the Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve.

