are statistically significant, the effect they have are not strong.

\section{\texorpdfstring{{Discussion}}{Discussion}}\label{sec-discussion}

There is no significant evidence to suggest that obesity rates in the
Scottish population change from 2013-2016. Table~\ref{tbl-yearmodel}
shows the proportions as relatively similar across years, and this is
further evidenced by the logistic regression model used to predict
obesity, as Figure~\ref{fig-log-odds} shows confidence intervals that
include 0, meaning there is very little difference in the log-odds
across the years. There are differences in obesity by age, gender,
socio-economic status, or lifestyle factors. This is evidenced by
Table~\ref{tbl-sex}, Figure~\ref{fig-age}, Table~\ref{tbl-edu},
Table~\ref{tbl-veg}, as all of these show a difference in obesity
prevalence within their own category. Furthermore, by being significant
predictors of obesity in the logistic regression model - \texttt{Age},
\texttt{Sex}, \texttt{Education}, and \texttt{Veg} must have significant
differences in obesity prevalence within their categories, otherwise
they would not be significant predictors, like \texttt{Fruit}.

\section{\texorpdfstring{{Conclusion}}{Conclusion}}\label{sec-conclusion}

In conclusion, there is no suggested evidence that obesity prevalence
has any significant chance over the years we considered in this report.
Moreover, there was evidence of a difference in obesity by age, gender,
socio-economic status, or vegetable consumption, however, no evidence of
a difference was observed by fruit.

